      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Leafs",
        "body": "The Leafs' season-long slide hit rock bottom with <strong>a gut-wrenching 5-6 overtime loss to Dallas on Saturday</strong>, their sixth straight defeat and a damning snapshot of a campaign careening toward the draft lottery. Sitting at 32-35-14 with 78 points, eighth in the Atlantic and 35 games back, Toronto's playoff dreams evaporated weeks ago&mdash;now it's all about clinging to that fifth spot in the lottery order, where their first-rounder stays home unless the ping-pong balls betray them to Boston. William Nylander's futile heroics&mdash;chasing pucks in a lineup that's forgotten how to win&mdash;can't mask the fatigue; the power play's gone cold, the defense a sieve. Every shift feels like auditioning for next year's roster. Tonight's tilt at Ottawa, locked in as WC2 against Carolina, is make-or-break: a Leafs win drops them to sixth (pending Seattle's stumbles), buying precious draft-position insurance with just days left before Thursday's finale. <strong>Win there, or watch the lottery odds slip further&mdash;because in Toronto, even elimination comes with a conditional asterisk.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated April 15, 2026"
      },
